If you try to send an unknown filetype, the notification string is broken (or just about anywhere else that mentions the filetype). The notification reads: "offered for download".

A quick fix that I didn't pull request because it's probably the wrong way to go about it, but it shows where the problem lies:

```patch
diff --git a/src/main/java/eu/siacs/conversations/utils/UIHelper.java b/src/main/java/eu/siacs/conversations/utils/UIHelper.java
index b00447a..016205f 100644
--- a/src/main/java/eu/siacs/conversations/utils/UIHelper.java
+++ b/src/main/java/eu/siacs/conversations/utils/UIHelper.java
@@ -175,7 +175,7 @@ public class UIHelper {
                try {
                        mime = URLConnection.guessContentTypeFromName(path);
                } catch (final StringIndexOutOfBoundsException ignored) {
-                       return "";
+                       return context.getString(R.string.file);
                }
                if (mime == null) {
                        return "";
diff --git a/src/main/res/values/strings.xml b/src/main/res/values/strings.xml
index e6776a6..c9d7223 100644
--- a/src/main/res/values/strings.xml
+++ b/src/main/res/values/strings.xml
@@ -363,6 +363,7 @@
     <string name="choose_file">Choose file</string>
     <string name="receiving_x_file">Receiving %1$s (%2$d%% completed)</string>
     <string name="download_x_file">Download %s</string>
+    <string name="file">file</string>
     <string name="open_x_file">Open %s</string>
     <string name="sending_file">sending (%1$d%% completed)</string>
     <string name="preparing_file">Preparing file for transmission</string>
```

Related: Shouldn't images also use the `UIHelper` methods? They still have their own separate strings.

